<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-num">09 — FAQ</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Wolf Repair FAQ</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much does Wolf appliance repair cost in Los Angeles?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Most Wolf repairs run $195–$680. Common fixes like a dual-stack igniter, door gasket, or temperature sensor are $175–$340. Control board or convection system work runs higher. Diagnostic fee is $89, waived when you proceed. Written flat-rate estimate before work begins.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can you service both Wolf and Sub-Zero in the same visit?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — and this is one of our key advantages. Wolf and Sub-Zero are both Sub-Zero Group brands, and many LA kitchens have both. We service the complete suite in a single visit: Wolf cooking equipment, Sub-Zero refrigeration, and Cove dishwasher. One call, one technician, one visit.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do you repair Wolf outdoor grills?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — Wolf outdoor grills and outdoor kitchen equipment are a specialty. LA's coastal salt air and year-round outdoor use create specific failure patterns we see regularly. We stock OEM Wolf outdoor components and perform full outdoor kitchen service including ignition, burner cleaning, valve inspection, and marine anti-corrosion treatment for coastal properties.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why does my Wolf oven temperature fluctuate?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Most Wolf oven temperature swings come from one of three causes: a worn door gasket (most common), a failing temperature probe, or a convection fan running at reduced or fixed speed. We test all three before ordering parts — a door gasket fix resolves roughly 40% of temperature calls and costs far less than a probe or motor replacement.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do you service Wolf ventilation hoods?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes. Wolf range hoods — wall, island, and integrated — are a dedicated service area. Common issues: blower motor failure, speed selector fault, and lighting. Importantly, a failed Wolf hood creates back-pressure that affects burner combustion on the range below. We check hood performance on every Wolf range service call.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How often should Wolf appliances be serviced in LA?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Annually for ranges and cooktops in active kitchens. Wolf ventilation hoods need duct and filter cleaning every 6–12 months depending on cooking volume. Outdoor grills need pre-season service — in LA that means every spring at minimum, and weatherproofing before the rainy season. Coastal properties should service outdoor equipment twice a year.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Are generic parts OK for Wolf appliances?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">No — particularly for ignition systems. Wolf's dual-stack burner igniters are geometry-specific. Generic igniters don't fit the dual-flame stack correctly and fail quickly under high-heat use. For door gaskets, temperature sensors, and control boards, generic parts also carry warranty and compatibility risks. We use only genuine Wolf OEM parts on every repair.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

